AMEND S e n ate Bill No. 2594* House Bill No. 2473
by deleting all language after the enacting clause and substituting:
SECTION 1. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 68, Chapter 1, is amended by adding
the following as a new part:
68-131-501. Short title.
This part is known and may be cited as the "Toxic-Free Medical Device Act."
68-131-502. Part definitions.
As used in this part:
(1) "DEHP" means di(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate, CAS No. 117-81-7;
(2) "Department" means the department of health;
(3) "Intentionally added" means the deliberate use of a chemical in the
formulation of a product if the chemical's continued presence in the product is
desired to provide a specific characteristic;
(4) "Intravenous solution container" means a container used to hold
medicine, fluid, or nutrition therapy for intravenous delivery to a patient in a
hospital, outpatient facility, or other healthcare facility;
(5) "Intravenous tubing" means tubing used to administer fluids,
medication, or nutrients intravenously to an adult, child, or infant; and
(6) "Ortho-phthalate" means a class of chemicals that are esters of ortho-
phthalic acid.
68-131-503. Prohibitions.
SA0967
016979
- 1 -

(a) On or after January 1, 2030, a person or entity shall not manufacture, sell, or
distribute in this state an intravenous solution container made with intentionally added
DEHP.
(b) On or after January 1, 2035, a person or entity shall not manufacture, sell, or
distribute in this state intravenous tubing made with intentionally added DEHP.
(c) To comply with this part, a person or entity shall not replace DEHP in a
medical device with another ortho-phthalate.
(d) A product does not violate this part if DEHP is present only as an
unintentional contaminant in a quantity that is less than one-tenth of one percent (0.1%)
weight by weight.
(e) A person or entity does not violate subsection (a) before January 1, 2032, if:
(1) The person or entity is unable to comply with subsection (a) by
January 1, 2030, because:
(A) Approval by the United States food and drug administration
for the DEHP-free intravenous solution container is pending; or
(B) The person or entity lacks adequate equipment to
manufacture the DEHP-free intravenous solution container;
(2) No later than October 1, 2026, the person or entity notified customers
in this state that the person or entity commenced development of the DEHP-free
intravenous solution container to comply with subsection (a); and
(3) No later than January 1, 2028, the person or entity:
(A) Notified customers in this state that such person or entity will
not meet the deadline in subsection (a); and
(B) Posted the notice required by subdivision (e)(3)(A) on the
person's or entity's official internet website.
68-131-504. Exemptions.
This part does not apply to:
- 2 - 016979

(1) Human blood collection and storage bags; or
(2) Apheresis and cell therapy blood kits and bags, including integral
tubing.
68-131-505. Rulemaking authority.
(a) The department may promulgate rules to implement and enforce this part in
accordance with the Uniform Administrative Procedures Act, compiled in title 4, chapter
5.
(b) Rules promulgated under this part may:
(1) Establish procedures for manufacturers to certify compliance with this
part;
(2) Define technical standards for testing medical devices for the
presence of DEHP or another ortho-phthalate;
(3) Establish a process for manufacturers to apply for a temporary
hardship extension of a compliance deadline if a manufacturer demonstrates that
a DEHP-free alternative is not commercially available or would compromise
patient safety; and
(4) Establish administrative penalties for violations of this part.
(c) Before the initial filing of rules under this section, the department shall consult
with the Tennessee Hospital Association and representatives of the medical device
manufacturing industry.
SECTION 2. The headings in this act are for reference purposes only and do not
constitute a part of the law enacted by this act. However, the Tennessee Code Commission is
requested to include the headings in any compilation or publication containing this act.
SECTION 3. For purposes of promulgating rules, this act takes effect upon becoming a
law, the public welfare requiring it. For all other purposes, this act takes effect July 1, 2026, the
public welfare requiring it.
